 221:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   *        The time source is configured to have 1ms time base with a dedicated
 222:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   *        Tick interrupt priority.
 223:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   * @note This function is called  automatically at the beginning of program after
 224:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   *       reset by HAL_Init() or at any time when clock is reconfigured  by HAL_RCC_ClockConfig().
 225:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   * @note In the default implementation, SysTick timer is the source of time base.
 226:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   *       It is used to generate interrupts at regular time intervals.
 227:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   *       Care must be taken if HAL_Delay() is called from a peripheral ISR process,
 228:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   *       The SysTick interrupt must have higher priority (numerically lower)
 229:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   *       than the peripheral interrupt. Otherwise the caller ISR process will be blocked.
 230:Drivers/STM32N6xx_HAL_Driver/Src/stm32n6xx_hal.c ****   *       The function is declared as __weak  to be overwritten  in case of other
